"""
MKT Context Commentary — Mark chapters 10–11
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-mark-10-11.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/mark.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/mark.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/mark.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Mark written for Roman Gentile audience (ca. 65-70 CE); explains Jewish customs
- Divorce debate (10:2-12) addressed to Pharisaic Hillel/Shammai controversy + Roman audience (v.12 addresses woman divorcing husband = Roman law, not Jewish)
- Children's low social status in antiquity explains disciples' rebuke (10:13)
- Camel/needle saying (10:25) is genuine hyperbole; no "Needle's Eye Gate" attested
- "Son of David" (10:47-48) is explicit Messianic title; first public use in Mark
- Triumphal entry (11:1-10) activates Zech 9:9 and Ps 118 Passover liturgy
- Fig tree / temple cleansing intercalation: the two events interpret each other
- Mark 11:26 is absent from earliest MSS (Sinaiticus, Vaticanus); scribal harmonization
- Authority question (11:27-33) is the Sanhedrin's formal challenge
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MARK = {
  "10": {
    "1": '<p>Jesus moves from Galilee to "the region of Judea and beyond the Jordan" — the area known as Perea (from the Greek <em>peraia</em>, "the far side"), the Transjordanian territory under Herod Antipas. This is the same region where John the Baptist operated and was killed; Jesus now enters it on his final journey toward Jerusalem. The crowds follow as in Galilee: the Galilean withdrawal of 7:24 and 8:27 is over — the public phase has resumed on the road south toward the capital.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The Pharisees\' question about divorce was not purely academic: it was a live controversy between the school of Shammai and the school of Hillel, two dominant interpretive traditions. Deuteronomy 24:1 permitted divorce when a husband found "something indecent" in his wife — the Shammaites interpreted "indecent" narrowly (only sexual immorality); the Hillelites interpreted it broadly (anything displeasing, including burning food). Jesus will sidestep both schools by appealing to creation before the Mosaic law. The Pharisees test him to see which school he will validate — or condemn.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"What did Moses command you?" — Jesus redirects from the Deuteronomic permission to the question of what Moses actually commanded. The Mosaic legislation on divorce (Deut 24:1-4) is in fact a regulation of divorce practice, not a command to divorce. It assumes divorce happens and regulates it; it does not endorse it. Jesus is probing whether the Pharisees can distinguish between what the law commanded and what it merely permitted under conditions of human moral failure.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The divorce certificate (<em>sefer keritut</em>, "document of cutting off") was a legal instrument whose primary function was to protect the woman: with a certificate in hand she had documented proof of her legally dissolved status and could remarry without being accused of adultery. The Mishnah (tractate <em>Gittin</em>) contains extensive regulations about the proper form, scribal execution, and delivery of the divorce document — the rabbis treated it as a serious legal matter, not a casual act. The Pharisees cite the certificate provision as evidence that divorce is Mosaic-sanctioned.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Because of your hardness of heart Moses wrote you this commandment" — Jesus\'s reinterpretation of the Mosaic divorce legislation as a concession to human moral failure rather than a positive institution is a significant hermeneutical move. The "hardness of heart" (sklērokardia) is a specific OT concept: in Deuteronomy it describes Israel\'s stubborn resistance to God\'s instruction (Deut 10:16, 30:6). The Mosaic law accommodated the reality of a community whose hearts had not been transformed; the kingdom Jesus announces operates on a different basis.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"From the beginning of creation God made them male and female" — Jesus appeals to Genesis 1:27 as the baseline for marriage. The argument from creation order as prior to and more authoritative than Mosaic legislation is a distinctive form of halakic reasoning: when God\'s original intent is recoverable, it takes precedence over later regulatory concessions. For Mark\'s Roman Gentile audience this argument would have been accessible without knowledge of the Hillel/Shammai debate: creation design as the norm for marriage.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The quotation of Genesis 2:24 ("For this reason a man will leave his father and mother and be united to his wife") moves from the creation of male and female to the institution of the marriage bond. The phrase "leave and cleave" established marriage as the primary human social bond — superseding even the parent-child relationship. In the Greco-Roman world where Jesus is speaking, the household (oikos) was the foundational social unit; the argument that the marital bond is the deepest human bond had social resonance beyond the Jewish legal context.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"The two will become one flesh" — the creation ordinance of Genesis 2:24, which Jesus treats as the defining description of what marriage is. The argument moves from anthropological to ontological: if two have become one flesh by God\'s act in marriage, then a human legal dissolution cannot undo what God has joined. The Mosaic divorce certificate is legally valid but cannot reverse the creation reality. The one-flesh language in Genesis was widely used in Jewish commentary as a description of the marital union\'s depth.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"What God has joined together, let no one separate" — a formal declarative statement with the weight of a legal pronouncement. The verb <em>suzeugnumi</em> ("to yoke together") was used in Hellenistic Greek for yoking animals as well as in figurative senses for matched pairs. The idea that God is the agent of the joining (not merely a witness to a human contract) grounds the prohibition of separation in divine action, not human law. This is the public statement; vv.10-12 provide the private elaboration for the disciples in the house.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The "house" (<em>oikia</em>) as the setting for private teaching is a recurring Markan pattern: public teaching addresses crowds, private teaching in the house addresses the disciples (cf. 7:17, 9:28, 9:33). The disciples\' private question suggests they were confused or troubled by the radical departure from accepted halakic practice. Jesus\'s teaching on divorce was more restrictive than even the strictest Shammaite position, which still permitted divorce for marital unfaithfulness.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Anyone who divorces his wife and marries another commits adultery against her" — the phrase "against her" (<em>ep\' autēn</em>) is significant: in Jewish law, adultery was defined as a wrong against a husband (using his wife), not against the wife herself. Jesus redefines adultery as a wrong committed against the woman — a radical reframing that grants the wife moral standing as an injured party in a way that standard Jewish and Roman legal frameworks did not.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"And if she divorces her husband and marries another, she commits adultery" — Jewish halakah did not recognize a woman\'s right to initiate divorce (the husband initiated by issuing the certificate). Roman law, however, permitted women to divorce their husbands, and this practice was common in elite Roman society. Mark\'s version of this saying addresses the Roman audience\'s actual social situation — women who could and did divorce. Matthew\'s version (19:9) addresses only the husband\'s initiative. Mark\'s inclusion of the reciprocal case confirms a Roman context.</p>',
    "13": '<p>People brought children (paidia — young children, possibly infants) to Jesus for the laying on of hands and blessing — a recognized practice for receiving rabbinic blessing. The disciples\' rebuke reflected the social reality: children in the ancient world had no legal standing, no honor, no social leverage. They were dependents, not persons in the full social sense. Wasting a teacher\'s time on those who could not reciprocate in the patron-client system made no social sense. Jesus\'s indignation (ēganaktēsen — strong word, also used in 10:41) corrects this social calculation entirely.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"The kingdom of God belongs to such as these" — not a romanticization of childhood innocence (an anachronistic reading) but a statement about social position. Children were the classic example of those with no status, no power, and no leverage — the paradigm of the socially powerless. The kingdom is theirs precisely because they bring nothing to claim it with. The same logic governs Jesus\'s beatitudes (the poor, the mourning, the meek): those who have nothing to commend themselves are the kingdom\'s primary recipients.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Anyone who will not receive the kingdom of God like a little child will never enter it" — the comparison is not to childlike faith in the sense of simplicity or trust but to the position of a child: one who must receive rather than earn, who has no standing to demand, who is wholly dependent on the giver\'s goodwill. The kingdom is received like a gift given to those who cannot reciprocate. The social inversion — the child as the kingdom\'s model recipient — subverts every honor-based calculation about who deserves the kingdom.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Jesus takes the children in his arms (enagkalisamenos — also at 9:36, a gesture of full embrace), places his hands on them, and blesses them. The laying on of hands for blessing was a recognized prophetic and rabbinic gesture; Numbers 27:18-23 records Moses laying hands on Joshua; Genesis 48:14-19 records Jacob\'s blessing of Joseph\'s sons by the same gesture. The physical action is not incidental: Jesus is formally bestowing blessing on those the social system had told to wait outside.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The encounter with the rich young man takes place on the road to Jerusalem — the journey section that structures Mark 8:27-10:52. The term "good teacher" in a Jewish context was not standard address for a rabbi: Jewish teachers said "good" of God but not of human teachers (b. Taanit 7a). The man\'s casual use of the title prompts Jesus\'s question about its meaning. The man\'s claim to have kept all the commandments from his youth would have been heard as a standard pious claim — the rabbis debated whether perfect Torah observance was achievable in principle (it was not a scandalous claim). Jesus\'s look and love (v.21) followed by the impossible demand makes the encounter a revelation about the nature of the heart\'s attachment to possessions.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Why do you call me good? No one is good except God alone" — the challenge is not a denial of divinity but a Socratic probe. The man has used "good" as a casual honorific without reflecting on what the word means. In Jewish discourse, goodness in the full and absolute sense was attributed to God alone (Ps 118:1, 136:1; cf. b. Taanit 7a). Jesus\'s response forces the questioner to either withdraw the compliment or face its implications: if goodness belongs to God alone, what is he calling Jesus?</p>',
    "19": '<p>The commandment list Jesus cites is from the second table of the Decalogue (duties to humans, Exod 20:12-16) — omitting the first table (duties to God). The addition of "do not defraud" (mē apostereisēs) is not from the Decalogue but from Leviticus 19:13 or Deuteronomy 24:14 (withholding wages). Its inclusion may be pointed: someone who has accumulated great wealth in a society where land acquisition often involved dispossessing small farmers would need to hear this specific prohibition. The commandments addressed are precisely those most relevant to a wealthy man\'s conduct toward others.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"All these I have kept since I was a boy" — keeping the commandments from youth was the ideal of Torah piety. The Mishnah records the merit of those who observed the commandments from their early years; Paul similarly claims blamelessness in his pre-Christian life (Phil 3:6). The man\'s claim is sincere, not boastful — he genuinely believes he has lived a life of Torah faithfulness. His question "What must I do to inherit eternal life?" reveals that this sincerity has not brought him the assurance of standing before God that he seeks.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Jesus looked at him and loved him" (emblepsas autō ēgapēsen auton) — the only place in Mark where Jesus is said to love a specific named individual. The love precedes and motivates the demand that follows; the call to sell everything is not a barrier to relationship but an act of love that offers liberation from what has become an idol. "One thing you lack" — the deficiency is not moral failure (he has kept the commandments) but a structural attachment that has made wealth his security rather than God. The verb <em>agapaō</em> here is the same as the great commandment to love God — what Jesus demonstrates toward the man is precisely what the man is unable to direct toward God fully.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The man "went away sad" (stugnasas, literally his face fell — the word means dark or gloomy; it appears in the LXX for the clouded faces of those in distress). The explanation is simple: "he had great wealth." The word <em>ktēmata</em> (possessions, estates, lands) indicates not cash but property — the accumulated capital of a landed family. The sadness is not mere greed; it is the genuine grief of someone who has encountered something true and found they cannot choose it. The encounter is unresolved in Mark; unlike the later tradition, there is no record of whether he ever returned.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Jesus looks around at his disciples and pronounces the principle: "How hard it is for the rich to enter the kingdom of God." In a Jewish culture that generally interpreted prosperity as a sign of divine favor (cf. Job\'s friends\' theology; the Deuteronomic blessing/curse framework), this statement was shocking. Wealth was expected to facilitate access to God, not impede it. The disciples\' amazement (v.24) reflects this cultural assumption: if the wealthy cannot be saved easily, what hope is there for anyone?</p>',
    "24": '<p>"Children, how hard it is to enter the kingdom of God" — Jesus broadens the statement from the rich specifically to everyone generally. The disciples are addressed as "children" (<em>tekna</em>) — the same word used for the children brought for blessing (v.13), and a term of pastoral address (as in 1 John 2:1). The hardness of kingdom entry is not unique to the wealthy: the rich are simply the clearest case of a universal problem. No one enters on the basis of their own resources, social standing, or merit.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The camel through the eye of a needle is genuine hyperbole expressing structural impossibility. The camel was the largest animal common to the region (Bactrian or dromedary); the needle\'s eye was the smallest functional opening in everyday life. The combination is an image of something that simply cannot happen. Later interpreters invented a "Needle\'s Eye Gate" in Jerusalem through which camels had to unload before passing — there is no archaeological or textual evidence for this gate. Some manuscripts substituted <em>kamilon</em> (rope or ship\'s cable) for <em>kamēlon</em> (camel) — either reading makes the same point. The saying means what it says: wealth makes kingdom entry humanly impossible.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The disciples are now "even more amazed" (perissōs exeplēssonto — intensified form of the standard amazement word) and ask each other, "Who then can be saved?" The question follows logically from the previous saying: if the wealthy (who have God\'s material blessing, by standard reasoning) cannot enter the kingdom, then no one can enter on the basis of their social standing. The question is genuine theological crisis, not mere intellectual puzzlement. The answer Jesus gives in v.27 does not resolve the crisis through qualification but through a statement about God\'s ability.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"With humans it is impossible, but not with God; all things are possible with God" — the saying echoes Genesis 18:14 (God\'s response to Sarah\'s laughter: "Is anything too hard for the LORD?") and Job 42:2 ("I know that you can do all things; no purpose of yours can be thwarted"). The grammar is emphatic: salvation is in the category of humanly impossible things that only God can accomplish. This is not a qualification of the camel/needle saying but its proper completion: the rich man cannot save himself; but God can save the rich man. The agency shifts entirely from human to divine.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"We have left everything to follow you" — Peter\'s interjection is the flip side of the rich man\'s departure: the disciples are those who did what the rich man could not. The word <em>panta</em> (everything) is the same as Jesus\'s demand to the rich man ("sell everything you have"). The disciples\' abandonment of their fishing businesses, homes, and family networks to follow an itinerant teacher was economically significant and socially unusual. Peter\'s question about reward for this investment is direct and not rebuked — it is an honest request for clarity about the terms of discipleship.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Jesus\'s response lists what the disciples have left: home, brothers, sisters, mother, father, children, fields — the totality of the kinship network and the economic base (fields). In a Mediterranean kinship society, these relationships were not merely sentimental; they constituted a person\'s entire social safety net, honor-network, and economic system. To leave them was not a minor personal choice but a fundamental restructuring of social existence. The "for me and the gospel" is the stated reason — not ambition or wanderlust but allegiance to the person of Jesus and his message.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The return is in the "present age" (en tō kairō toutō): homes, brothers, sisters, mothers, children, and fields — but with persecutions. The new kinship network (the community of disciples) replaces the old one, but persecutions are built into the promise. Mark does not offer a Christianity without suffering; the reward of community comes packaged with persecution, because the community follows a crucified Lord in a world that killed him. "In the age to come, eternal life" completes the promise — the ultimate inheritance that the rich man asked about in v.17 is given to those who could not give it to themselves.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Many who are first will be last, and the last first" — a reversal saying that appears in different contexts across the Gospels (Matt 19:30, 20:16; Luke 13:30) and appears to be a free-standing aphorism Jesus applied to multiple situations. Here it follows the discussion of wealth, status, and discipleship rewards: the social inversions of the kingdom are not exceptional cases but systematic. Those who have positioned themselves advantageously by the world\'s metrics will find those metrics reversed; those who have abandoned social advantage will find themselves in a new and different position of honor.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"They were on their way up to Jerusalem, with Jesus leading the way, and the disciples were astonished, while those who followed were afraid" — the journey from Jericho to Jerusalem involved an ascent of roughly 1,050m over 27km, one of the steepest roads in the region. The geographic "going up" mirrors the theological weight of the journey: Jerusalem is the holy city, but also the place of death. The astonishment of the Twelve and the fear of the wider followers are appropriate responses to someone walking deliberately toward what he has just predicted (vv.33-34). Jesus leads; the others follow at a distance.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"The Son of Man will be delivered to the chief priests and teachers of the law" — the third passion prediction is the most specific and detailed of the three (cf. 8:31, 9:31). It names: (1) the delivering agent (implied: Judas), (2) the recipients (chief priests, scribes), (3) their action (condemnation to death), (4) handover to Gentiles (Romans), (5-7) three forms of humiliation (mocking, spitting, flogging), (8) death, (9) resurrection. The sequence matches the actual passion narrative precisely. The council of priests and scribes who condemned Jesus and the Roman execution that followed are both anticipated here.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The three forms of degradation — mock, spit, flog — constitute a systematic humiliation sequence. Mocking attacked honor; spitting was the most degrading gesture of contempt available in the ancient world (Num 12:14; Job 30:10; Isa 50:6 — the last of which connects this prediction to the Servant Songs); flogging was the Roman preparatory punishment before crucifixion (verberatio). The prediction is given to those who have just heard James and John ask for places of honor: the glory they are asking to share is this.</p>',
    "35": '<p>James and John\'s request comes immediately after the third passion prediction — the structural juxtaposition is Mark\'s sharpest irony. They have just heard that Jesus will be mocked, spat on, flogged, and killed; they respond by asking for the seats of highest honor in his glory. The request to sit at the right and left in "your glory" (<em>en tē doxē sou</em>) uses the language of the Messianic kingdom — in a Davidic royal court, the positions at the king\'s right and left hand were the highest seats of authority and proximity (1 Kgs 2:19).</p>',
    "36": '<p>"What do you want me to do for you?" — the same question Jesus will ask Bartimaeus in v.51, but the answers will be entirely different. The question is not rhetorical; Jesus genuinely asks what they want. The contrast between the disciples\' self-advancing request and the blind beggar\'s request for sight structures the closing scenes of the journey section: one asks for status, the other for the capacity to see. Only one gets what he asks for.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"Let one of us sit at your right and the other at your left in your glory" — the honor-positioning request reflects the Mediterranean patron-client social logic operating even within the discipleship group. First-century readers would have recognized the request immediately: in royal court protocol, the right and left hand positions were reserved for the king\'s most trusted associates. The disciples are competing within a system of honor that Jesus is about to redefine. Ironically, the "right and left in glory" will be occupied at the crucifixion by two criminals (15:27).</p>',
    "38": '<p>"You don\'t know what you are asking. Can you drink the cup I drink or be baptized with the baptism I am baptized with?" — both images carry OT freight. The "cup" in prophetic literature is often the cup of God\'s wrath or suffering (Ps 75:8, Isa 51:17, Jer 25:15-17); Jesus uses it for his own coming death (14:36). "Baptism" as immersion in overwhelming suffering appears in Psalm 69:1-2 and Isaiah 43:2. To share Jesus\'s cup and baptism is to share his suffering and death — not his glory in isolation from his cross. James and John say they can, and are told they will.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"You will drink the cup I drink and be baptized with the baptism I am baptized with" — Jesus\'s answer is not a rebuke but a promise. Both James and John will indeed suffer for the gospel: James was the first apostolic martyr (Acts 12:2, killed by Herod Agrippa I ca. 44 CE); John, by tradition, was exiled to Patmos and outlived all the other apostles. Both drank the cup, in different ways. The grant of seats at right and left, however, is not Jesus\'s to give — it belongs to those "for whom it has been prepared" (by God, implied passive).</p>',
    "40": '<p>The statement that the seats of honor are "not for me to grant" is one of the more theologically striking in Mark: it implies a limit on what the Son will assign. The preparation of these positions belongs to the Father (cf. Matt 20:23 makes this explicit: "my Father has prepared"). This is consistent with Mark\'s Christology of the Son\'s subordination within the mission: the Son does the Father\'s will, not his own (14:36). The seats of the kingdom are part of the Father\'s prerogative to allocate.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The other ten disciples become indignant with James and John — not because the request was wrong in principle but because James and John moved first. The competitive dynamics of a group competing for positions in a future honor hierarchy is exposed: the ten are angry not about honor-seeking but about being cut out of the competition. The indignation gives Jesus the occasion for a teaching that addresses not just James and John but the entire group\'s orientation toward power and greatness.</p>',
    "42": '<p>"You know that those who are regarded as rulers of the Gentiles lord it over them" — Jesus begins with an observation about how authority functions in the Gentile world, which is the world his Roman audience inhabits. The verb <em>katakyrieousin</em> ("lord it over") describes the downward exercise of power from the powerful to the powerless. "High officials exercise authority over them" (<em>katexousiazousin</em>) — the compound with <em>kata-</em> prefix emphasizes the dominant, hierarchical direction of power. This is not a false description of how Roman imperial power worked; it is accurate.</p>',
    "43": '<p>"Not so with you. Instead, whoever wants to become great among you must be your servant (<em>diakonos</em>)" — the term <em>diakonos</em> designated someone who served at table or ran errands for another; it was the lowest rung of the household service ladder. In the honor-shame framework, the person who served tables was at the bottom of the social hierarchy. Jesus is not merely recommending humility as a virtue but inverting the entire definition of greatness: social status in the kingdom of God is measured in the opposite direction from Gentile power structures.</p>',
    "44": '<p>"Whoever wants to be first must be slave (<em>doulos</em>) of all" — <em>doulos</em> intensifies the inversion: not merely a hired servant (<em>diakonos</em>) but a slave — a person with no legal standing, no social honor, and no personal freedom. The hierarchy is: all → first, many → great, slave → free. The kingdom\'s ranking system operates in reverse. This is not advocating for actual slavery as a social institution but using the most extreme example of social subordination available to make the point about the radical inversion of status in the kingdom.</p>',
    "45": '<p>"For even the Son of Man did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many" — the ransom saying grounds the servant-leadership teaching in Jesus\'s own example. <em>Lytron</em> (ransom) was a commercial term for the price paid to free a slave or prisoner of war; it required a payment made to a holder of someone in bondage. "For many" (<em>anti pollōn</em>) uses the preposition <em>anti</em> meaning "in place of" or "as a substitute for" — a substitutionary exchange. The "many" echoes Isaiah 53:11-12 ("he will justify many... he bore the sin of many"), tying the ransom saying to the Servant Songs of Isaiah.</p>',
    "46": '<p>Jericho is one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world, located in the Jordan valley at approximately 250m below sea level — the lowest city on earth. The Roman-era city (distinct from the OT city tell) was built by Herod the Great as a winter palace site and was a prosperous urban center. The road from Jericho to Jerusalem was 27km and climbed roughly 1,050m — a significant ascent that pilgrims walked annually for the Passover. Bartimaeus is identified by name (bar Timaeus = son of Timaeus), unusual for a healed person in Mark, suggesting he was known in the early Christian community.</p>',
    "47": '<p>"Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!" — <em>huie Dauid</em> is the Messianic title in Jewish usage, designating the expected descendant of David who would restore the Davidic kingdom (2 Sam 7:12-16; Ps 2; Amos 9:11). This is the first time in Mark that the title is applied to Jesus by name in public. The cry for mercy (<em>eleēson</em>) echoes the Kyrie eleison (Lord, have mercy) of liturgical tradition. Bartimaeus is not confused about who Jesus is or what he can do: he addresses him with the highest available title and asks for the most basic need.</p>',
    "48": '<p>Many in the crowd rebuke Bartimaeus and tell him to be quiet — the crowd\'s attempt to suppress a public Messianic acclamation on the road to Jerusalem. The Messianic title in a public pilgrimage procession to Jerusalem could trigger political alarm (Roman soldiers would be on alert for Passover-related agitation). Bartimaeus shouts all the more: his persistence in the face of the crowd\'s rebuke mirrors the shameless prayer of the friend at midnight (Luke 11:8) and the persistent widow (Luke 18:1-8). In an honor-shame culture, shameless persistence in public was itself a form of social assertion.</p>',
    "49": '<p>Jesus stops — the entire procession halts for a blind beggar. "Call him" — the crowd\'s role reverses immediately from rebuke to summons. "Cheer up! On your feet! He\'s calling you" — three quick commands conveying the shift from rejection to welcome. The social dynamics of the scene are precise: the crowd that had been suppressing Bartimaeus is now the vehicle of Jesus\'s call to him. The one who was silenced is now summoned to the center.</p>',
    "50": '<p>Throwing off his cloak (<em>himation</em>) — a beggar\'s cloak spread on the ground was his collection device: coins would be thrown into it. To throw it aside and jump up is to abandon the instrument of his livelihood in response to the call. The action parallels the disciples\' abandonment of their nets (1:18, 20): the immediate physical relinquishment of the tool of one\'s economic survival in order to come to Jesus. Bartimaeus has nothing else; he leaves even that behind.</p>',
    "51": '<p>"What do you want me to do for you?" — the same question asked of James and John in v.36. The contrast is pointed: two disciples asked for positions of power and honor in the kingdom; a blind beggar asks for sight. Both are addressed with the same patient question; only one request is granted. The blind man\'s request is simple and specific — "Rabbi, I want to see" (<em>rabbouni</em>, an Aramaic intensive form meaning "my great teacher," used only here and at John 20:16). The address is more intimate than the Messianic "Son of David" of v.47.</p>',
    "52": '<p>"Go, your faith has healed you" — the same formula as the hemorrhaging woman (5:34), the ten lepers (Luke 17:19). Bartimaeus immediately receives his sight and follows Jesus "along the road" — the discipleship journey toward Jerusalem. He is the last person healed in Mark before the passion narrative begins; his following Jesus "on the road" places him in the procession ascending to Jerusalem. The healing of the blind man concludes a journey section (8:22-10:52) bookended by two healings of blindness — the section in which the disciples have repeatedly failed to see what the text demonstrates.</p>'
  },
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>Bethphage ("house of unripe figs") was a village near the summit of the Mount of Olives, east of Jerusalem; Bethany ("house of dates" or "house of the poor") was on the eastern slopes of the Mount of Olives, about 3km from Jerusalem — the village of Mary, Martha, and Lazarus (John 11). The Mount of Olives (754m) rises east of Jerusalem across the Kidron valley, with a clear view of the temple complex. Zechariah 14:4 predicted that "the LORD will stand on the Mount of Olives" in the day of judgment — the approach from the east via the Mount of Olives carried eschatological freight for Jewish pilgrims who knew the prophecy.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The village ahead is identified in Luke 19:29 as Bethphage. A colt (pōlos — a young horse or donkey, in this context a donkey) that "no one has ever ridden" would be ritually appropriate for a sacred purpose: in the OT, animals used for holy purposes were required to be ones that had never been yoked or worked (Num 19:2; Deut 21:3; 1 Sam 6:7). The instruction to untie it and bring it suggests a prior arrangement: the phrase "the Lord needs it and will send it back shortly" functions as a code or password established in advance.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"The Lord needs it" (<em>ho kyrios autou chreian echei</em>) — the phrasing is ambiguous: "the Lord" could refer to Jesus (using a Christological title) or to the colt\'s owner (in the sense of "its master needs it back"). Either reading is coherent in context. The arrangement suggests advance planning: Jesus has organized the colt\'s availability as part of a deliberate entry into Jerusalem that enacts Zechariah 9:9 ("your king comes to you, gentle and riding on a donkey"). The entry is not spontaneous but staged as a prophetic action.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The colt found "outside in the street, tied at a doorway" — a street-level detail that suggests genuine topographic memory. The location is specific: not inside a courtyard but at the street entrance. The casual precision of this detail (the kind of thing an eyewitness would remember) is consistent with the Petrine tradition that Mark preserves. The disciples\' execution of the instruction without incident confirms the prior arrangement.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Bystanders ask "What are you doing, untying that colt?" — the challenge is from people present at the scene, not the owners. In Mediterranean village culture, community members monitored public space and would question anyone removing property that did not obviously belong to them. The challenge is not hostile but socially normative: the bystanders are exercising the communal oversight function that village social structure expected. The disciples\' response (quoting Jesus\'s exact instruction) resolves the question immediately.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The people "let them go" — the password worked. Whether they were the owners or simply knew of the arrangement, the phrase "the Lord needs it" was sufficient. The smooth execution of the pre-arranged transaction is notable: there is no confusion, no negotiation, no resistance. The colt is released without further incident, confirming the advance arrangement. The narrative efficiency here is deliberate: the focus is on the entrance itself, not on the logistics of the colt.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Throwing cloaks over the colt was a practical measure (an unridden colt would not have been saddled) but also a gesture with royal resonance. 2 Kings 9:13 records that when Jehu was acclaimed king, his followers spread their garments under his feet as a gesture of submission and homage. The disciples\' action reenacts this royal installation gesture — they are participating in an enthronement procession, with the colt as the royal mount and their cloaks as the royal carpet.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Cloaks spread on the road and branches cut from the fields — the collective response of a Passover crowd to a figure they are treating as a royal arrival. Palm branches (specifically named in John 12:13) were a symbol of Judean independence and victory, used at the Maccabean rededication of the temple (1 Macc 13:51; 2 Macc 10:7). Their use during the Passover pilgrim procession carried both political (independence from Rome) and liturgical (festival celebration) connotations. Mark does not specify palms but "branches cut from the fields" — whatever was available from the surrounding vegetation.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Hosanna!" is a transliteration of the Hebrew <em>hoshi\'ah-na</em>, "save now/please," from Psalm 118:25. The Hallel Psalms (113-118) were sung during Passover; Psalm 118 was specifically the pilgrim psalm for those arriving at Jerusalem from outside. "Blessed is he who comes in the name of the LORD" (v.26 of Ps 118) was the formula used to welcome incoming pilgrims — the Levites would chant it from the gates as the procession arrived. The crowd is using standard Passover liturgy, but applying it to Jesus as the specific one who comes.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Blessed is the coming kingdom of our father David! Hosanna in the highest heaven!" — these additions to Psalm 118:26 are explicitly Messianic: the crowd is not merely greeting a pilgrim but identifying the moment as the arrival of the Davidic kingdom. "Our father David" is the expected ancestor of the Messiah; "the coming kingdom" is the eschatological expectation. The shout "Hosanna in the highest" redirects the plea from the crowd to heaven — calling on God to save from the highest place. The combination is an unmistakable Messianic demonstration in a city full of pilgrims for Passover.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The reconnaissance visit: Jesus enters Jerusalem, enters the temple courts, and surveys everything (<em>periblepsámenos</em> — "looked around at everything," the word of deliberate comprehensive inspection). The late hour means it is too late to act; he withdraws with the Twelve to Bethany for the night. The survey is purposeful: Jesus is planning. The withdrawal to Bethany (where he stayed throughout Passover week; Josephus notes that the surrounding villages were included in the Passover zone) suggests a base of operations outside the city where he could rest and prepare.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The fig tree episode (11:12-14 and 11:20-25) brackets the temple cleansing in one of Mark\'s characteristic intercalations. Near Bethany, walking back toward Jerusalem the next morning, Jesus is hungry. Figs in Palestine ripen fully in June; at Passover (late March/early April) trees would have new leaves but no ripe fruit. However, the first green figs (<em>paggim</em> in Hebrew) that accompany the early leaves were edible even before full ripeness. Their absence means this tree was not producing even preliminary fruit — it had the appearance of fruitfulness (leaves) without substance.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Mark\'s explanatory note — "because it was not the season for figs" — is often cited as a textual difficulty: why curse a tree for lacking figs out of season? The note may be from Mark explaining to a non-Palestinian Gentile audience why an early fig was not expected. Alternatively, the note emphasizes the irony: even out of season, a fig tree with leaves and no figs is an image of false advertising — the appearance of life without its reality. In OT prophecy, the unfruitful fig tree is a consistent image for Israel\'s failure to produce the covenant faithfulness that its formal religious practices promised (Jer 8:13, Hos 9:10, Mic 7:1).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"May no one ever eat fruit from you again" — the curse is a prophetic acted parable, intelligible only in retrospect (when the tree is found withered the next day, 11:20). The disciples "heard him say it" — a mark of eyewitness report. The curse is pronounced on the road to the temple; the temple action follows immediately (vv.15-19); the withering is discovered on the return (vv.20-25). The structural meaning of the intercalation: the temple institution (like the fig tree) bears the appearance of covenant life (sacrifices, prayers, commerce supporting worship) without the fruit God requires.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The temple complex in Jerusalem (Herod\'s temple, begun 20 BCE, not completed until 63 CE — just 7 years before its destruction) was enormous: the Temple Mount platform covered approximately 36 acres. The Court of the Gentiles (the outermost court, open to non-Jews) was where the money-changers and animal sellers operated. The Tyrian shekel was required for the half-shekel temple tax because its silver purity was reliable; pilgrims coming from across the diaspora needed to exchange their local currency. The commerce occupied the only space designated for Gentile prayer, effectively excluding the nations from the one place in the temple complex that was theirs. Mark\'s preservation of "for all nations" (Isa 56:7) makes the exclusion explicit.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"He would not allow anyone to carry merchandise through the temple courts" — a detail unique to Mark, absent from Matthew and Luke. The Court of the Gentiles (the outermost precinct) was being used as a commercial shortcut between the city and the eastern areas (the Kidron valley, the road to Bethany). Carrying goods through the sacred precinct treated it as a marketplace thoroughfare rather than a house of prayer. Jesus\'s prohibition of this transit use is a demand that the space be treated as holy — not as a financial convenience. The detail suggests an eyewitness memory of the specific topography.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"My house will be called a house of prayer for all nations" — the citation is from Isaiah 56:7, which in its original context is one of the most universalist passages in the OT: foreigners who hold fast to God\'s covenant will be welcomed to his holy mountain, their sacrifices accepted. The "for all nations" clause (present in Mark, absent from Matthew\'s citation of the same verse) emphasizes the inclusion of Gentiles as the violated intent of the temple. "Den of robbers" is from Jeremiah 7:11 (the "temple sermon"), where Jeremiah accused Israel of hiding behind the temple while practicing injustice — treating the temple as a magical guarantee of security regardless of conduct.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The chief priests and teachers of the law seek to kill Jesus — the official response is immediate and decisive. Their motive is specified: "they feared him, because the whole crowd was amazed at his teaching." The mechanism is social-political: they cannot act against him publicly without triggering a riot, because he has too much popular support. The word for "feared" (<em>ephobēsan</em>) carries both the sense of political apprehension and deeper dread. The temple authorities are caught between their desire to eliminate him and the crowd that makes elimination impossible in this setting.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The pattern of leaving the city at evening and returning in the morning (cf. 11:11-12, 11:19-20) reflects both the practical reality of Passover Jerusalem (the city was overcrowded with pilgrims; the Mishnah records regulations about accommodating the increased population, and Bethany was within the halachically defined "greater Jerusalem" for Passover purposes) and Jesus\'s deliberate management of the situation: presence in the city during the day for teaching and confrontation; withdrawal to the Mount of Olives area at night for safety and rest.</p>',
    "20": '<p>On the morning walk from Bethany to Jerusalem, the disciples see the fig tree "withered from the roots" (<em>exērantai ek rizōn</em>). The completeness of the withering — from the roots, not just the branches — confirms that this is not natural die-back but a total and immediate death. The disciples\' recognition of the specific tree they passed yesterday ("look, the fig tree you cursed!") establishes continuity between the two scenes. The intercalation is now complete: the temple has been cleansed and the fig tree has died; the two actions illuminate each other.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Rabbi, look! The fig tree you cursed has withered!" — Peter remembers the curse (v.14: "his disciples heard him say it") and makes the connection. The address "Rabbi" (<em>rhabbi</em>) is the standard respectful address for a teacher; in Mark it appears on Peter\'s lips at the Transfiguration (9:5) and here. The disciples\' astonishment at the rapid withering frames the teaching that follows: Jesus uses their surprise as an entry point into a teaching on faith, prayer, and forgiveness that connects to the authority demonstration just completed in the temple.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"Have faith in God" (<em>echete pistin theou</em>) — the instruction following the withered fig tree is about trust in God\'s power to accomplish what appears impossible. The fig tree was cursed by word; it withered. The teaching unpacks what this means for the disciples\' own capacity to speak and pray with expectation. The instruction is not about commanding nature arbitrarily but about living in confident dependence on God\'s word having the power to accomplish what it declares — which is what Jesus has just demonstrated.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The mountain-moving saying is a Jewish idiom for accomplishing something extremely difficult. The rabbis called an exceptional teacher who could resolve apparently impossible halakic problems a "rooter up of mountains" or "mountain remover" — a figure of speech for overcoming what seemed insuperable obstacles. Jesus radicalizes the idiom: not just as a description of remarkable teaching ability but as a description of what trusting prayer actually does. The specific image — "say to this mountain, Go, throw yourself into the sea" — may have had topographical resonance on the Mount of Olives overlooking the Dead Sea, though it is primarily proverbial.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"Whatever you ask for in prayer, believe that you have received it, and it will be yours" — the grammar of "believe that you have received it" (aorist, already accomplished) describes trust that anticipates completion. Jewish prayer at this period was typically formulaic (the Amidah, the Eighteen Benedictions) but also included personal petition. The teaching does not provide a technique for prayer but describes the posture of trust from which effective prayer flows: not trying to leverage God into compliance, but speaking from the foundation of confidence in what God has said he will do.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"When you stand praying, if you hold anything against anyone, forgive them" — standing was the standard Jewish prayer posture (not kneeling or prostration; cf. Luke 18:11-13; 1 Sam 1:26). The connection between prayer and forgiveness appears in the Lord\'s Prayer tradition (Matt 6:12,14-15) but here without the Lord\'s Prayer itself, as a freestanding instruction. The logic is the same: the person who holds unforgiveness is asking for God\'s mercy while refusing to extend mercy — a structural contradiction that blocks the prayer before it begins.</p>',
    "26": '<p>This verse is absent from the earliest and most reliable manuscripts of Mark (Codex Sinaiticus, Codex Vaticanus, and several other early witnesses) and is widely recognized by textual scholars as a scribal harmonization with Matthew 6:15 ("But if you do not forgive others their sins, your Father will not forgive your sins"). The verse was inserted by copyists to complete the thought from v.25 in explicit parallel with Matthew. Though present in later manuscripts and the KJV tradition, it was almost certainly not part of Mark\'s original text.</p>',
    "27": '<p>They arrive again in Jerusalem — the third consecutive morning return to the city (11:11, 12, 27). "While Jesus was walking in the temple courts" — public, deliberate, visible presence in the space he had cleansed two days earlier. The delegation that approaches him represents the supreme judicial authority: chief priests, scribes, and elders together constitute the Sanhedrin (the full council of 71 that governed Jewish religious and civil life in Jerusalem under Roman oversight). This is not an informal challenge but a formal institutional interrogation of his authority.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"By what authority are you doing these things?" — "these things" refers to the entry into Jerusalem, the temple cleansing, and the teaching that followed. The Sanhedrin has authority to examine prophets, teachers, and would-be Messiahs; the question is legitimate. In Jewish legal understanding, authority to act in a religious capacity required either official appointment (priestly ordination, rabbinic ordination) or prophetic commission from God. Jesus has no official appointment; the only alternative is divine commission. The question is: which does he claim, and can he prove it?</p>',
    "29": '<p>"I will ask you one question. Answer me, and I will tell you by what authority I am doing these things" — the counter-question strategy is a recognized rabbinic technique (<em>teshuvat ha-sheilah</em>, answering a question with a question). It was considered legitimate as a teaching device, especially when the questioner has not earned the right to a direct answer. Jesus\'s counter-question about John is not an evasion: it is a test of whether the council can adjudicate a clear case of divine versus human authority. If they cannot evaluate John, they have no standing to evaluate Jesus.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"John\'s baptism — was it from heaven or of human origin?" — the question is perfectly calibrated. John\'s baptism was a public, known phenomenon; its reception by the entire population of Judea and Jerusalem (1:5) was a matter of record. The question of its origin is exactly parallel to the question they asked about Jesus: was it divinely authorized or merely human initiative? The council must evaluate a closely analogous case before proceeding with Jesus\'s case. Their answer will reveal whether they have the capacity — and the willingness — to evaluate genuine divine authority at all.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The council\'s private deliberation reveals a group reasoning from consequences rather than from truth: "If we say from heaven, he will ask why we didn\'t believe him." This is not a bad-faith evasion but an accurate description of their situation — they did not respond to John with belief (cf. Matt 21:32; Luke 7:30) and they know it. The trap is of their own making: they cannot acknowledge John\'s divine authority without condemning their own prior failure to respond to him, and they cannot deny it without alienating the people.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"If we say \'of human origin\'..." — the sentence trails off, unfinished in the text, because the problem is obvious: everyone held John to be a genuine prophet, and denying his divine commission would put the council against the entire Jewish public. John\'s death had made him a popular martyr; challenging his prophetic status in public would be politically suicidal. The council is caught between institutional self-protection (they cannot admit they were wrong about John) and popular pressure (they cannot deny what everyone knows). Both options destroy them.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"We don\'t know" — a formal pleading of ignorance in a legal setting. By admitting they cannot evaluate John\'s authority, the council surrenders the ground from which they could evaluate Jesus\'s authority. Jesus\'s response — "neither will I tell you by what authority I am doing these things" — is not evasion but a formal matching: they have withheld their judgment on a clear case; he withholds his answer to their question. The exchange ends in a public draw, but the moral weight is entirely on Jesus\'s side: they know the answer but will not say it; he refuses to justify himself before a court that has demonstrated bad faith.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, MARK)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Mark mkt-context chs 10-11: {total} verses total written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
